øøøøøøøøøøøøø                                 DRAPER PASCALøø                                  Version 2.1øø                                 Copyright 1989ø                                 by Norm Draperøøø               For the Atari 400, 800, XL, or XE series computersøøøøøøøøøøøøøø                            Disk Based Documentationøø       This document contains the "Getting Started" section plus otherø       sections from the actual Draper Pascal manual.  It is designed toø       get you up and running and doing useful things with Draper Pascalø       in a very short time.  It does not, however, contain a detailedø       description of all the Draper Pascal definitions or pretend to beø       a comprehensive tutorial or user's reference.  Registered usersø       will receive the actual Draper Pascal manual which does contain aø       complete description of all definitions plus other information.ø       Details on registering are in the last section titledø       "Registration Form".øøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøø       Draper Pascal 2.1                              Table of Contentsøøøøø                               Table of Contentsøø       The ShareWare Concept ---------------------------------  2ø       Features ----------------------------------------------  3ø       Introduction ------------------------------------------  5ø         What is Pascal? -------------------------------------  5ø         What is Draper Pascal? ------------------------------  5ø         About this manual -----------------------------------  5ø         What is Draper Pascal made of? ----------------------  5ø         About the DOS ---------------------------------------  6ø         Ramdisk support -------------------------------------  6ø       Getting Started ---------------------------------------  7ø       The Main Menu ----------------------------------------- 14ø         1 - Run Program ------------------------------------- 15ø         2 - Disk Directory ---------------------------------- 15ø         3 - Compile Program --------------------------------- 15ø         4 - Edit a Program ---------------------------------- 15ø         5 - Exit to DOS ------------------------------------- 15ø         6 - List a file ------------------------------------- 16ø         7 - Trace on ---------------------------------------- 16ø       The Editor -------------------------------------------- 17ø         General Prompts ------------------------------------- 18ø         The Commands ---------------------------------------- 19ø           A - Add line(s) at end ---------------------------- 19ø           C - Change line(s) -------------------------------- 19ø           D - Delete line(s) -------------------------------- 19ø           E - Edit line(s) ---------------------------------- 20ø           F - Filer menu ------------------------------------ 20ø             A - Append file --------------------------------- 20ø             D - Directory list ------------------------------ 20ø             L - Load file ----------------------------------- 20ø             S - Save file ----------------------------------- 21ø           I - Insert before line ---------------------------- 21ø           L - List line(s) ---------------------------------- 21ø           M - Menu ------------------------------------------ 21ø           P - Print line(s) --------------------------------- 21ø           Q - Quit ------------------------------------------ 22ø           S - Scan line(s) ---------------------------------- 22ø           X - Exit to Compiler ------------------------------ 22ø       The Compiler ------------------------------------------ 23ø       The Supervisor ---------------------------------------- 26ø       Pascal Definitions ------------------------------------ 27ø       System Information ------------------------------------ 32ø       Reserved Word List ------------------------------------ 33ø       Operators --------------------------------------------- 34ø       Error Messages ---------------------------------------- 35ø       Registration Form ------------------------------------- 38øøøøøøøøøø                                       1øøøøø       Draper Pascal 2.1                          The Shareware Conceptøøøøø                             The Shareware Conceptøø       Draper Pascal is distributed on a Shareware basis.  You may useø       Draper Pascal without charge for the purpose of evaluating it'sø       suitability for your use. If you find that Draper Pascal is worthø       continuing to use, then you are requested to become a registeredø       user and gain the additional benefits that go along with it.ø       Simply complete the registration form and mail it in to us withø       the very reasonable payment of only $15.00. When you register yourø       copy of Draper Pascal, you'll receive the latest version of theø       software if your registered version is not current, along with aø       comprehensive printed user manual.øø       If you have received this copy from a Users' Group, "Softwareø       Library" or "SIG", and have paid a small fee (usually $3 to $10),ø       you have NOT acquired the registered rights or continued right toø       use Draper Pascal. This fee was for the convenience of obtainingø       the diskette with Draper Pascal on it. The fee does NOT apply toø       the registration fee.øø       You may freely copy Draper Pascal for distribution under theø       Shareware concept, without charge.øø       You may NOT charge any fee for the Draper Pascal program orø       documentation without our written approval.øø       You may NOT distribute Draper Pascal or it's documentation inø       connection with ANY commercial venture, product, publication orø       service unless you obtain the royalty-free license byø       registering.øøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøø                                       2øøøøø       Draper Pascal 2.1                                       Featuresøøøøø                                    Featuresøø       *  Draper Pascal is a complete package allowing the user toø          create, compile, and execute programs written in the Pascalø          language.øø       *  Many features from both UCSD and ISO standard Pascals plus manyø          extensions, such as sound and graphics, to make use of theø          versatile Atari hardware.øø       *  Pascal structured programming features, including IF-THEN-ELSE,ø          WHILE-DO, CASE-OF-ELSE, FOR-TO/DOWNTO-DO, and REPEAT-UNTIL areø          included.øø       *  FUNCTIONs and PROCEDUREs using local or global variables.ø          Integer type variables can be passed directly.øø       *  Data types supported include: Character, String, Integer, Real,ø          Boolean, Record, and File.  One and two dimension arrays areø          also supported for all data types other than File and Record.øø       *  Only one disk drive and 48K RAM are required. Multiple, andø          double density, disk drives are supported.øø       *  Machine language subroutines may be loaded and called.øø       *  Program chaining is supported.øø       *  No limit on source program size.  "Include" files areø          supported.øø       *  One-pass compiler generates pseudo code directly.øø       *  Maximum program pseudo code size is about 30K bytes.øø       *  Textual compiler error messages.øø       *  Execution debugging features include instruction trace andø          stack display.øø       *  Special options for error display and break key disable.øø       *  Single keystroke program execution repeat, exit to DOS, or exitø          to Main Menu program are featured.øø       *  Includes Editor program to create, modify, and print Pascalø          source files, or other text type files.øø       *  Includes Main Menu program (Pascal source included) for easyø          select of Compiler, Editor, or utility functions, such asø          directory or file listing. Main Menu program may be replacedø          with a user written program to create a turnkey operation.øøøøø                                       3øøøøø       Draper Pascal 2.1                                       Featuresøøøøø       *  Ramdisk support. Details provided to registered users.øø       *  Works with most popular versions of DOS.øø       *  Easy to use. No linking required.  Compile and executeø          immediately.øø       *  Royalty free license available to registered users.øø       *  Includes sample programs.øø       *  Comprehensive user manual provided to registered users.ø          Complete examples and BASIC equivalents given for each reservedø          word.øøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøø                                       4øøøøø       Draper Pascal 2.1                                   Introductionøøøøø                                  Introductionøø       Draper Software welcomes you to the world of Pascal for the Atariø       400/800, XL, and XE series Computer systems.øø                                What is Pascal?øø       Pascal is a high-level structured programming language developedø       by Niklaus Wirth in 1971. It is easy to understand and well suitedø       for program development and maintenance.øø                             What is Draper Pascal?øø       Draper Pascal is not a "standard" Pascal. It has a number ofø       commands which are exactly like ISO and UCSD versions, some whichø       are similar, and many "extensions" which bring out the true powerø       of the Atari computer in an easy to use manner. It was designed toø       require only one disk drive for operation, but not be limited toø       only one. At this time, it has been shown to work with allø       hardware and software configurations where enough memory isø       provided. This implementation also has a number of commands whichø       are familiar to Atari BASIC users, such as POKE, PEEK, SETCOLOR,ø       NOTE, POINT, etc..øø                               About this manualøø       This manual is intended to familiarize you with all the featuresø       of Draper Pascal. It is not intended to teach you how to programø       in Pascal. However, if you already know Atari BASIC, then you canø       understand the Pascal statements more easily by referring to theirø       BASIC equivalents shown after the definition of each Pascalø       reserved word in the complete manual provided to registered users.ø       It is recommended that you read this manual completely to beø       familiarized with its features and restrictions.øø                         What is Draper Pascal made of?øø       This implementation of Pascal is made up of three main components.ø       They are the Supervisor (sometimes referred to as runtimeø       routines), the Compiler, and the Editor. The Supervisor is a highø       performance machine language program which simulates a 16-bitø       pseudo computer. The Compiler translates Pascal source code intoø       pseudo-code instructions to be executed by the Supervisor. Theø       Editor is used to enter and modify Pascal source programs. It mayø       also be used to edit data files, or BASIC programs which have beenø       LISTed to a disk or tape. These components are explained in detailø       within this manual.øø       For a description of the various files included on the suppliedø       diskette, refer to the 'System Information' section.øøøøøøø                                       5øøøøø       Draper Pascal 2.1                                   Introductionøøøøø                                 About the DOSøø       Draper Pascal can be used with most popular Disk Operatingø       Systems. It has been tested with Atari DOS 2.5, SpartaDOS 3.2d,ø       and MYDOS. You should format a diskette with DOS on it to containø       the Draper Pascal system. Since the Draper Pascal Supervisor isø       named AUTORUN.SYS, it will execute immediately after the disk isø       booted. For XL and XE computers, you do not need to hold down theø       Option key while booting unless you are using SpartaDOS. If usingø       SpartaDOS, you may want to rename AUTORUN.SYS to PASCAL.COM andø       create a STARTUP.BAT file containing the following two lines:øø         BASIC OFFø         PASCALøø       This documentation file is not required to be on that sameø       diskette.øø                                Ramdisk supportøø       Draper Pascal supports the use of the "Ramdisk" capabilityø       provided by using a DOS that supports a ramdisk like Atari DOS 2.5ø       or SpartaDOS 3.x with an Atari computer system having sufficientø       memory to support the ramdisk. While using this feature, theø       Editor takes less than two seconds to load and the Compiler takesø       less than three seconds. Details on setup and use of this featureø       are provided in the complete manual provided to registered users.øøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøø                                       6øøøøø       Draper Pascal 2.1                                Getting Startedøøøøø                                Getting Startedøø       This section is intended to show by example how to use the Draperø       Pascal system. You will edit, compile, and run a sample program.ø       Information displayed by the computer is shown in normal typeø       while responses to be entered by you are shown underlined withø       dashes (---). To begin with, make sure you have 48K RAM installedø       and no cartridge in place. Boot the disk now by placing it in diskø       drive 1 and turning on the power to the Atari computer. After theø       Supervisor has finished loading, you will see a screen that looksø       like this:øøøø                  DRAPER PASCALøø                   VERSION 2.1øø               1 - Run Programøø               2 - Disk Directoryøø               3 - Compile Programøø               4 - Edit a Programøø               5 - Exit to DOSøø               6 - List a fileøø               7 - Trace onøøøø                  Copyright 1989ø                  by Norm Draperøøøøø               4                              Select the Editorø               -øøøøøøøøøøøøøøø                                       7øøøøø       Draper Pascal 2.1                                Getting Startedøøøøø                 DRAPER SOFTWAREø                     EDITORøøø               A - Add line(s) at endø               C - Change line(s)ø               D - Delete line(s)ø               E - Edit a lineø               F - Filer menuø               I - Insert before lineø               L - List line(s)ø               M - Menuø               P - Print line(s)ø               Q - Quitø               S - Scan line(s)ø               X - Exit to Compilerø       A,C,D,E,F,I,L,M,P,Q,S,X,?->F           Select Filer menuø                                  -øøø               A - Append fileø               D - Directory listø               L - Load fileø               S - Save fileøø               L                              Load a fileø               -øøø       Enter filename  -> SAMPLE1             Enter the name of the fileø                          -------             to be loaded. The name ofø                                              the last file edited,ø                                              compiled, or run will beø                                              filled in by the Editor.ø                                              You may have to overtypeø                                              it with the name shown.øøøø       A,C,D,E,F,I,L,M,P,Q,S,X,?->L           List the file on theø                                  -           screenøø       Line from ->                           Just press RETURN forø                   -                          'Line from' and 'Line to'.ø       Line to   ->                           This will give a list ofø                   -                          the entire program inø                                              memory.øøøøøøøøøø                                       8øøøøø       Draper Pascal 2.1                                Getting Startedøøøøøø         1:PROGRAM KALEIDOSCOPE;ø         2:VAR I,J,K,W,X:INTEGER;ø         3:BEGINø         4: MAXGRAPH(19);ø         5: GRAPHICS(19);ø         6: X:=0;ø         7: REPEATø         8: FOR W:=3 TO 50 DOø         9:  BEGINø        10:    FOR I:=1 TO 10 DOø        11:    BEGINø        12:     FOR J:=0 TO 10 DOø        13:      BEGINø        14:       K:=I+J;ø        15:       COLOR(J*3/(I+3)+I*W/12);ø        16:       PLOT(I+8,K);ø        17:       PLOT(K+8,I);ø        18:       PLOT(32-I,24-K);ø        19:       PLOT(32-K,24-I);ø        20:       PLOT(K+8,24-I);ø        21:       PLOT(32-I,K);ø        22:       PLOT(I+8,24-K);ø        23:       PLOT(32-K,I)ø        24:      ENDø        25:    ENDø        26:  ENDø        27: UNTIL X=99 (* UNENDING LOOP *)ø        28:END.ø       A,C,D,E,F,I,L,M,P,Q,S,X,?->I           Let's insert a commentø                                  -           before line 15.ø       Line -> 15ø               --øø        15:       (* MY FIRST EDIT *)         Enter the data to beø                  -------------------         inserted when prompted forø        16:                                   line 15. Just press RETURNø            -                                 when prompted for line 16.ø                                              This will terminate insertø                                              mode.øø       A,C,D,E,F,I,L,M,P,Q,S,X,?->L           List again to verify thatø                                  -           the change was madeø                                              correctly.øø       Line from ->ø                   -ø       Line to   ->ø                   -øø         1:PROGRAM KALEIDOSCOPE;ø         2:VAR I,J,K,W,X:INTEGER;øøøøø                                       9øøøøø       Draper Pascal 2.1                                Getting Startedøøøøø         3:BEGINø         4: MAXGRAPH(19);ø         5: GRAPHICS(19);ø         6: X:=0;ø         7: REPEATø         8: FOR W:=3 TO 50 DOø         9:  BEGINø        10:    FOR I:=1 TO 10 DOø        11:    BEGINø        12:     FOR J:=0 TO 10 DOø        13:      BEGINø        14:       K:=I+J;ø        15:       (* MY FIRST EDIT *)ø        16:       COLOR(J*3/(I+3)+I*W/12);ø        17:       PLOT(I+8,K);ø        18:       PLOT(K+8,I);ø        19:       PLOT(32-I,24-K);ø        20:       PLOT(32-K,24-I);ø        21:       PLOT(K+8,24-I);ø        22:       PLOT(32-I,K);ø        23:       PLOT(I+8,24-K);ø        24:       PLOT(32-K,I)ø        25:      ENDø        26:    ENDø        27:  ENDø        28: UNTIL X=99 (* UNENDING LOOP *)ø        29:END.ø       A,C,D,E,F,I,L,M,P,Q,S,X,?->F           Let's save the programø                                  -           back to disk drive 1ø                                              under the same name.øø               A - Append fileø               D - Directory listø               L - Load fileø               S - Save fileøøø               Sø               -ø       Enter filename  -> SAMPLE1ø                          -------ø       A,C,D,E,F,I,L,M,P,Q,S,X,?->X           Now let's exit directly toø                                  -           the Compiler.øøøøøøøøøøøøøø                                       10øøøøø       Draper Pascal 2.1                                Getting Startedøøøøø                Draper Softwareøø                Pascal Compilerøø                  Version 2.1øøø                Copyright 1989ø                by Norm Draperøøøø                Enter Filename:ø                SAMPLE1                       Enter name of program toø                -------                       be compiled. The name ofø                                              the last program edited,ø                                              compiled, or run will beø                                              filled in by theø                                              Compiler.øø       Enter List Output Filespecø       Default is E:                          Just press RETURN at thisø                    -                         point to have the compileø                                              list directed to theø                                              screen.øø       0000 PROGRAM KALEIDOSCOPE;ø       0000 VAR I,J,K,W,X:INTEGER;ø       0003 BEGINø       0003  MAXGRAPH(19);ø       0017  GRAPHICS(19);ø       001B  X:=0;ø       001E  REPEATø       0022  FOR W:=3 TO 50 DOø       002A   BEGINø       0035     FOR I:=1 TO 10 DOø       003D     BEGINø       0048      FOR J:=0 TO 10 DOø       004F       BEGINø       005A        K:=I+J;ø       0062        COLOR(J*3/(I+3)+I*W/12);ø       008A        PLOT(I+8,K);ø       0098        PLOT(K+8,I);ø       00A6        PLOT(32-I,24-K);ø       00B8        PLOT(32-K,24-I);ø       00CA        PLOT(K+8,24-I);ø       00DC        PLOT(32-I,K);ø       00EA        PLOT(I+8,24-K);ø       00FC        PLOT(32-K,I)ø       010A       ENDø       010A     ENDø       010C   ENDøøøøø                                       11øøøøø       Draper Pascal 2.1                                Getting Startedøøøøø       011C  UNTIL X=99 (* UNENDING LOOP *)ø       0142 END.ø       0147ø       ADDR   NAMEø       ---- --------ø       0003 Iø       0004 Jø       0005 Kø       0006 Wø       0007 Xø       5 Compiler table entries usedø       *** Program Execution Completed ***    Press the SELECT key atø       Highest Stack Address Used = $AFF8     this point to take us toø       <START>Repeat,<SELECT>Menu,<ESC>Exit   the main menu.øø                  DRAPER PASCALøø                   VERSION 2.1øø               1 - Run Programøø               2 - Disk Directoryøø               3 - Compile Programøø               4 - Edit a Programøø               5 - Exit to DOSøø               6 - List a fileøø               7 - Trace onøøøø                  Copyright 1989ø                  by Norm Draperøøø              1                               Select '1' to run theø              -                               program that was justø                                              compiled.øø         Enter name of program to be runøø              SAMPLE1                         The name of the lastø              -------                         program edited, compiled,ø                                              or run will be filled inø                                              by the main menu program.ø                                              Overtype the name if youø                                              want to run a differentø                                              program.øøøøø                                       12øøøøø       Draper Pascal 2.1                                Getting Startedøøøøøø       =================================================================øøø       At this point you should have a nice kaleidoscope pattern beingø       displayed on your television screen. To stop it, press the BREAKø       key. To repeat execution, press the START key. To return to theø       main menu, press the SELECT key. To exit to DOS, press the ESCø       key.øø       Another program, SAMPLE2, is also provided for you to practiceø       with. It will display Roman numerals for powers of two between 1ø       and 4096. Compile it, turn on the trace via the main menu, and runø       it. After it is finished, press CTRL-T to display the trace table,ø       and CTRL-S to display the stack contents. When prompted forø       'Where? Filespec', enter 'E:'. For a description of the stackø       display line, refer to the 'DUMPSTK' command in the 'Pascalø       Definitions' section of the manual provided to registered users.øøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøø                                       13øøøøø       Draper Pascal 2.1                                      Main Menuøøøøø                                   Main Menuøø       The Main Menu is the initial program to be run by the Supervisor.ø       It is written in Pascal. The source code is provided for it andø       you may customize it as you see fit. The disk filename for theø       source is 'INIT.PAS'. The pseudo code program that is initiallyø       executed is 'INIT.PCD'. It would be wise to copy 'INIT.PCD' toø       another name to be used in case your compile of the menu programø       is not successful. Or, you could rename INIT.PAS to somethingø       else, like NEWINIT.PAS, and compile it to produce NEWINIT.PCD.ø       Then you can use the 'run' option (mentioned below) to test yourø       modified program.øø       The Main Menu appears as follows:øø                  DRAPER PASCALøø                   VERSION 2.1øø               1 - Run Programøø               2 - Disk Directoryøø               3 - Compile Programøø               4 - Edit a Programøø               5 - Exit to DOSøø               6 - List a fileøø               7 - Trace onøøøø                  Copyright 1989ø                  by Norm Draperøøø       Each of the menu options will now be explained:øøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøø                                       14øøøøø       Draper Pascal 2.1                                      Main Menuøøøøø       1 - Run Programøø       Use this option to execute a program that has previously beenø       successfully compiled. You will see the following prompt:øø       Enter name of program to be runøø       The Main Menu program will fill in the name of the last programø       edited, compiled, or run. If this is the one you want, all youø       have to do is press RETURN. If it is not the one you want, justø       overtype the name shown with the one you want.øøø       2 - Disk Directoryøø       This option will provide you with a list of all, or selected,ø       files on one of your disk drives. You will receive the promptø       'Filespec?'. If you just press RETURN at this point, you will seeø       a list of all files on the default drive. If you enter 'D2:', youø       will see all files on drive 2. To show only selected files, useø       wildcards in the normal manner. For example, enter 'D1:INIT.*' toø       show only files named INIT with any suffix from drive one. At theø       end of the list, you will be prompted to press any key toø       continue. After pressing any key, the Main Menu will beø       re-displayed.øøø       3 - Compile Programøø       This option sends you directly to the Pascal compiler. You will beø       prompted for the name of the program to be compiled, after theø       Compiler is loaded. If you have already edited, compiled, or run aø       program, the name will be shown and may be used by just pressingø       the RETURN key. For more information, refer to the section of thisø       manual on 'The Compiler'.øøø       4 - Edit a Programøø       Control is transfered to the Draper Pascal Editor when this optionø       is chosen. For more information, refer to the section of thisø       manual on 'The Editor'.øøø       5 - Exit to DOSøø       Pascal execution is terminated by this option. Control is passedø       to the Disk Operating System.øøøøøøøøø                                       15øøøøø       Draper Pascal 2.1                                      Main Menuøøøøøø       6 - List a fileøø       This convenience entry is provided to allow you to view, on theø       screen, any text file on disk or tape. You are prompted to enterø       the name of the file to be listed. The file is assumed to resideø       on the default drive if a colon (:) is not found within the nameø       you specify. At the end of the list, you will be prompted to pressø       any key to continue. After pressing a key, the Main Menu willø       appear again.øøø       7 - Trace onøø       The wraparound internal trace may be turned on (or off) with thisø       option. The trace is used only for debugging purposes and may beø       viewed at program termination time by pressing CTRL-T. Programø       execution speed is slightly degraded while the trace is active.ø       You will be prompted to enter the number of trace entries to beø       maintained by the system. Each trace entry requires 10 bytes ofø       storage at the high end of memory. The trace may not be usedø       during graphics displays because screen memory is also at the highø       end of memory. To turn the trace off and remove the memoryø       allocation of the trace table, enter zero when prompted for theø       number of entries to maintain. The trace format is described inø       the manual provided to registered users.øøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøø                                       16øøøøø       Draper Pascal 2.1                                     The Editorøøøøø                                   The Editorøø       The Editor is used to create, modify, and save Pascal sourceø       files. It may also be used to process other text type files, likeø       BASIC programs which have been LISTed to disk or tape. It is aø       line oriented editor. Combined with some type of formattingø       program, it may be used for word processing applications. Theø       entire source to be edited must be in memory at one time. If yourø       Pascal program will not fit within the limits of the Editor, thenø       you can use the INCLUDE feature of the Compiler to allow segmentsø       of a program to be edited separately. Refer to the section on "THEø       COMPILER" for more information on the INCLUDE feature. Source codeø       for the Editor is listed in the manual provided to registeredø       users. Some key points to be noted about this editor are asø       follows:øø       1.  Each line is referred to by line number, however, no lineø           numbers are stored either internally or on the disk or tape.øø       2.  Each line may contain up to 80 characters. This may be changedø           by altering the constant called MAXLENGTH and re-compiling theø           Editor. A source listing of the Editor is provided toø           registered users.øø       3.  A maximum of 250 lines of text may be edited at one time. Thisø           may be changed by altering the constant called MAXLINES andø           re-compiling the Editor. An increase in MAXLINES shouldø           correspond with a decrease in MAXLENGTH, and vice versa. Aø           source listing of the Editor is provided to registered users.øø       4.  When entering or editing a line, the line must be terminatedø           by pressing the RETURN key.øø       5.  As lines are inserted into, or deleted from, the source file,ø           the remaining lines are automatically renumbered.øø       6.  A line of source may extend onto more than one screen line.øø       7.  Due to operation of the Atari operating system, a blank lineø           may not be directly entered. To enter a blank line, you mustø           first enter a non-blank character (like a period), then useø           the Editor Change command to change the character to a space.øø       8.  Input operations (Append and Insert) are terminated byø           entering a null line (just pressing the RETURN key).øø       9.  The BREAK key is disabled by the Editor to prevent loss ofø           data. It is enabled again at termination of the Editor.øøøøøøøøø                                       17øøøøø       Draper Pascal 2.1                                     The Editorøøøøø       10. If you enter or change data then try to Quit or exit to theø           Compiler without first saving the data onto disk, you willø           receive an option to either save the data or ignore it andø           continue.øø       11. Cassette tape files may be loaded, edited, and saved by theø           Editor. The Compiler does not support tape input, though. Youø           would first have to load the file from tape, with the Editor,ø           then save it to disk.øøøø                                EDITOR COMMANDSøøøø                                General Promptsøøø       The following prompts are general in nature and are common amongø       many of the editor commands to be described below.øø       Line ->øø       You are prompted to enter one line number, as opposed to a rangeø       of line numbers. It is used by the INSERT Editor command andø       refers to the line before which the inserted line(s) will beø       placed.øø       Line from ->øø       This is the first prompt for a range of line numbers. Enter theø       low number of the range. If you just press RETURN, line number 1ø       is assumed.øø       Line to   ->øø       Enter the high line number in the range desired. If only one lineø       is to be acted upon, that number must be entered in both thisø       prompt and the one mentioned above. If you just press RETURN, theø       highest line number in the buffer will be assumed. If the numberø       you enter is less than the 'Line from' value, the 'Line from'ø       value will be used here.øøøøøøøøøøøøøø                                       18øøøøø       Draper Pascal 2.1                                     The Editorøøøøø       Enter filename  ->øø       This prompt is shown when loading, appending, and saving files.ø       The last filename used is filled in after the arrow. If this isø       the file you wish to use now, then all you have to do is pressø       RETURN. A full filespec may be entered, but is not required. If aø       colon (:) is not found within the filename specified, then theø       default drive is assumed. If the filename given does not contain aø       period (.), then a suffix of .PAS is assumed.øø                                  The Commandsøøø       A - Add line(s) at endøø       This command is used to add lines after the last line currently inø       the buffer. If the buffer is currently empty, then line 1 will beø       assumed as the starting point. In this manner, you can create aø       new file if one has not been loaded. You can append as many linesø       as you like. When you are finished entering lines, just pressø       RETURN without entering any data on the line (null line).ø       Prompts used: Noneøø       C - Change line(s)øø       The Change command allows you to change one specified stringø       pattern to another for the first occurance in each line within theø       range of lines specified. After being prompted for the line numberø       range, you are asked for the data to 'Change from ->' and 'Changeø       to   ->'. Enter any string of characters at each prompt. Imbeddedø       blanks are allowed. If you just press RETURN for the 'Change to'ø       prompt, the first occurance of the 'Change from' data within eachø       line will be deleted.ø       Prompts used: 'Line from', 'Line to', 'Change from', 'Change to'øø       D - Delete line(s)øø       This command allows you to delete a line or a range of lines fromø       the file in memory. The whole file in memory will be deleted ifø       you just press RETURN when prompted for both 'Line from' and 'Lineø       to'. Be aware that all lines following the range deleted will beø       renumbered, to fill the gap just made. If you desire to delete aø       number of line ranges, delete those with the highest numbers firstø       and proceed toward the beginning of the file. That way, you won'tø       have to do a LIST after each range delete to find out what the newø       line numbers for the following lines are.ø       Prompts used: 'Line from', 'Line to'øøøøøøøøøø                                       19øøøøø       Draper Pascal 2.1                                     The Editorøøøøøø       E - Edit line(s)øø       The Edit command is used to edit (or make individual changes to) aø       line or range of lines that already exist in memory. If a range isø       specified, the lines are presented to you one at a time. As eachø       line is presented, you may use any of the normal Atari editingø       keys (like right and left cursor, insert, delete), to alter theø       data. Just press RETURN when you are finished with each change. Ifø       you don't want to make a change to a line shown, just pressø       RETURN.ø       Prompts used: 'Line from', 'Line to'øø       F - Filer menuøø       The Filer is a subsystem which handles communication with anø       external device (disk or tape). The features provided are asø       follows:øø           A - Append fileøø           A file is read from disk or tape and added to the end of theø           file currently in memory. The data in memory prior to theø           append remains unchanged.ø           Prompts used: 'Enter filename'øø           D - Directory listøø           This command is used to provide a directory list of theø           different files on a diskette. You are prompted forø           'Filespec?'. Enter the disk drive number and selectionø           criteria for the directory list. If you just press RETURN youø           will see a directory list of all files on the default drive.ø           To see all files on drive two, enter 'D2:' or 'D2:*.*'. To seeø           only files with a suffix of PAS on drive one, enterø           'D1:*.PAS'.ø           Prompts used: 'Filespec?'øø           L - Load fileøø           This is the way to load a file into memory from disk or tape.ø           If any data was currently in memory, it is deleted andø           replaced by the file read in.ø           Prompts used: 'Enter filename'øøøøøøøøøøøøø                                       20øøøøø       Draper Pascal 2.1                                     The Editorøøøøøø           S - Save fileøø           Data is copied from memory to disk or tape with this command.ø           The data currently in memory remains unchanged. You areø           prompted for filename and may use whatever name you wish. Itø           is not necessary to save a file under the same name as wasø           used to load the file. You should save data to disk frequentlyø           if you are making extensive changes. That way you won't haveø           to re-do as much if something goes wrong.ø           Prompts used: 'Enter filename'øø       I - Insert before lineøø       This command allows you to insert one or more lines at any pointø       within the file in memory. The inserted data is placed before theø       line number you specify. To terminate insert mode, just pressø       RETURN without entering any data on the same line (null line).ø       Note that all lines after the point of insertion willø       automatically be renumbered.ø       Prompts used: 'Line ->'øø       L - List line(s)øø       One or more lines of data from memory are listed on the screenø       with this command. During the list, you may stop the scrolling byø       pressing either the space bar or RETURN. To resume scrolling,ø       press any other key other than ESC. The ESC key may be pressed toø       prematurely terminate the listing.ø       Prompts used: 'Line from', 'Line to'øø       M - Menuøø       The main Editor menu is presented in response to this command. Aø       question mark (?) may also be used to display the main menu.ø       Prompts used: Noneøø       P - Print line(s)øø       This command is used to create a list of data in memory on aø       printer attached to the Atari parallel port (P:). Internal lineø       numbers are also directed to the printer although they do notø       actually exist within the file on disk or tape.ø       Prompts used: 'Line from', 'Line to'øøøøøøøøøøøøø                                       21øøøøø       Draper Pascal 2.1                                     The Editorøøøøøø       Q - Quitøø       This command is used to exit from the Editor when you are finishedø       editing your data.  Control is given to the Main Menu program. Ifø       you have changed the data in memory and have not saved it prior toø       quitting, you will be given the option of saving the data orø       ignoring the changes and exiting. If you are going to compile aø       Pascal program immediately after quitting the Editor, you may useø       the 'X' command described below.ø       Prompts used: Noneøø       S - Scan line(s)'øø       This command allows you to display all lines within a specifiedø       range which contain a specified character string. The characterø       string may contain any characters, including imbedded blanks. Toø       temporarily stop the listing, press either the space bar orø       RETURN. To abort the listing, press ESC. Press any other key toø       continue as normal.ø       Prompts used: 'Line from', 'Line to', 'Scan for'øø       X - Exit to Compilerøø       This command terminates the Editor and transfers control directlyø       to the Compiler. If the file in memory has been changed but notø       saved prior to the Exit command, you will be prompted to eitherø       save the file or ignore the changes and proceed to the Compiler.ø       Prompts used: Noneøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøø                                       22øøøøø       Draper Pascal 2.1                                   The Compilerøøøøø                                  The Compilerøø       The Compiler is used to translate words that we humans understandø       into "words" that the computer can understand. The computer wordsø       are referred to as pseudo-code, or p-code for short. Theseø       pseudo-code instructions are understood and executed by theø       Supervisor.øø       This is a single pass goal oriented compiler. It expects theø       proper syntax for a statement. If correct syntax is not found, theø       compilation stops, and an error number with associated textø       description is displayed. At this point, you are given the optionø       of quitting or returning to the Editor to correct the problem andø       do the compile again.øø       The Compiler itself is written in Draper Pascal and occupies aboutø       28K of RAM memory space.øø       The first prompt from the Compiler is 'Enter filename:'. The nameø       of the last program edited, run, or compiled is filled in for yourø       convenience. If this is the one you want, just press RETURN. If itø       is not the one you want, just overtype it with the name youø       desire. The name you provide will become the new default name forø       the Editor, Compiler, and Main Menu 'Run' option. No suffix isø       allowed when specifying filename. The Compiler will add theø       standard '.PAS' to it for you. If the source does not reside onø       the default disk drive, then you must prefix the filename withø       'Dn:' where 'n' is the disk drive number where the source resides.ø       The default disk drive is normally disk drive number one, but isø       changed to the Ramdisk drive number if you are taking advantage ofø       the Ramdisk feature of a Disk Operating System that supports it.ø       Ramdisk initialization is explained in the manual provided toø       registered users.øø       The next prompt is 'Enter List Output Filespec'. The default (ifø       you just press RETURN) is the screen (E:). The list output may goø       to any normal output device, such as printer (P:) or diskø       (D:LISTNAME.PRN).øø       A number of additional points are mentioned below:øø        1. Comments are delimited by '(*' on the left end and '*)' on theø           right end. Any characters may appear within comments. Commentsø           may appear anywhere within the program.øø        2. 'Include' files are supported. You may have procedures,ø           functions, or any part of a program included in a compile,ø           even though it is not actually part of the file beingø           compiled. It is a variation of a comment which allows you toø           do this. The format is as follows:øø           (*$I XXXXXXXX *) or (*$I D1:XXXXXXXX *)øøøøø                                       23øøøøø       Draper Pascal 2.1                                   The Compilerøøøøøø           The dollar sign and 'I' must be right next to '(*' and must beø           followed by one space. Then you may mention the 'D' for diskø           and drive number (if other than the default drive is to beø           used). Follow it with a colon (:) and the filename. A suffixø           of '.PAS' will be automatically added to the file name. Thenø           have at least one space and '*)'.øø        3. Pascal source files must reside on disk.øø        4. The output pseudo-code from the compile will be directed toø           the same disk drive that the Pascal source resides on. It willø           be created with a filename suffix of '.PCD'. If you haveø           multiple disk drives and the source and pcode will not bothø           fit on one disk, have a small file on the output disk with anø           'include' for the source which resides on the other disk.øø        5. The hexadecimal offset of the pseudo instructions generated isø           given at the left side of the output listing. This offset mayø           be useful for debugging purposes. It may be referred to whenø           looking at a program trace (see TRACEON in the Pascalø           Definitions section of the manual provided to registeredø           users). It also may be referred to in case of an error messageø           or termination caused by pressing the BREAK key. The offsetø           shown may not always be accurate. If not exact, the values areø           very close.øø        6. The name and stack offset of each variable defined is shown atø           the end of the compile listing. The offset value is shown inø           hexadecimal. Each stack entry is two bytes wide. The firstø           three stack entries are reserved for system use. Therefore,ø           the offset of the first variable will be 0003, which isø           actually six bytes into the stack. If a variable is definedø           within a procedure or function, the offset shown is relativeø           the beginning of that procedure or function.øø        7. The program is ready to run immediately after the compile isø           finished. No linking is required. (Some Pascal systems requireø           linking of output code after the compile and beforeø           execution).øø       8.  Nested procedures are supported. You may define one procedureø           within another.øø       9.  Recursive procedures are supported. A procedure may callø           itself. If variables are defined within the procedure, theyø           are cleared with each entry into the procedure and refreshedø           upon exit from the recursive procedure call.øø       10. No forward references are allowed. A procedure may not beø           referenced before it is defined. In most cases, nesting theø           procedures will take care of this problem.øøøøø                                       24øøøøø       Draper Pascal 2.1                                   The Compilerøøøøøø       11. Double density disk drives are supported for both source andø           pcode files. The pcode will be written to the same drive thatø           the initial source is taken from.øø       12. Only integer type parameters may be passed to procedures andø           functions. Other types of data may be passed by using globalø           type variables setup at the beginning of the program (notø           within a procedure or function).øø       13. A function may only return an integer type value. Proceduresø           do not return values.øø       14. Hexadecimal constants and literals are prefixed by dollarø           signs ($).øø       15. To write out an integer in hexadecimal format, precede theø           variable name with a percent sign (%).øø       16. A total of 170 compiler table entries may be used. One tableø           entry is used for each variable definition, procedure name,ø           function name, and parameter name used with procedures andø           functions. Table entries for variables defined withinø           procedures are re-used following the 'END' for that procedure.ø           The number of table entries used within a compile is displayedø           at the end of the output list from the Compiler.øø       17. The time needed to compile a program can be reduced by turningø           off the ANTIC chip within the computer. This turns off theø           display to the screen yet gives a fairly significant increaseø           to the Atari's internal speed. In a normal Pascal program, youø           can have POKE(559,0) to turn it off and POKE(559,34) to turnø           it back on. But a special compile time option is provided toø           make use of this feature to speed up compiles. It is asø           follows. Have a statement (*$S+*) to turn the ANTIC offø           (increase speed), and use (*$S-*) to turn the ANTIC on (resumeø           normal speed). These options may appear anywhere within aø           program. The ANTIC is automatically turned back on at compileø           termination and at time of error (if any).øøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøø                                       25øøøøø       Draper Pascal 2.1                                 The Supervisorøøøøø                                 The Supervisorøø       The Supervisor is a high performance machine language programø       which simulates a pseudo 16-bit stack oriented computer. Itø       executes the pseudo code that is generated by the Compiler.øø       It is loaded into memory by disk operating system at the hexø       location $1D7C, which is just above DOS in memory. It should workø       with any DOS that allows a program to load at that address, suchø       as Atari DOS 2.1S, Atari DOS 2.5, or SpartaDOS version 2.x orø       higher. A message will be displayed if the Supervisor cannot beø       loaded at the proper location.øø       The disk filename for the Supervisor's object code isø       'AUTORUN.SYS'. It may be renamed to anything you desire, such asø       'PASCAL.COM', but will not be automatically loaded when the diskø       is booted if the name is other than 'AUTORUN.SYS'. To start theø       Pascal system from the DOS menu, use the 'L', binary load, optionø       to load 'AUTORUN.SYS' into memory. Execution will beginø       automatically.øø       The Supervisor begins execution by loading and executing theø       Pascal program 'INIT.PCD' from the default drive, which is alwaysø       disk drive 1 immediately after loading the Supervisor. 'INIT.PCD'ø       is the name of the main menu program. You may substitute anyø       compiled Pascal program of your own by naming it 'INIT.PCD'. Inø       this manner, you can have a true turnkey system where your programø       begins execution after booting the disk.øø       After termination of each Pascal program, the Supervisor gives youø       a choice of what to do next. You are prompted with the followingø       line:øø       <START>Repeat,<SELECT>Menu,<ESC>Exitøø       If you press the START key, your Pascal program will execute againø       from the beginning. If you press the SELECT key, control will beø       transfered to the main menu program (INIT.PCD). If you press theø       ESC key, you will exit to the DOS utility menu. You also have twoø       other options at this point. They are both used for debuggingø       purposes. If you press CTRL-S (the 'S' key while holding down theø       CTRL key), the stack values, at termination time, will beø       displayed. If you press CTRL-T, the internal trace table, ifø       active, will be displayed. With either of these two debuggingø       options, you will be asked where the display should be sent by theø       prompt 'WHERE? (FILESPEC)'. To see it on the screen, enter 'E:'.ø       It also may be sent to printer or disk by following normalø       filespec naming conventions. If the display is sent to the screen,ø       you may stop the scrolling by use of the space bar. Press the ESCø       key if you have seen enough and wish to return to the Supervisorø       termination prompt. Any other key causes scrolling to continue asø       normal.øøøøø                                       26øøøøø       Draper Pascal 2.1                             Pascal Definitionsøøøøø                               Pascal Definitionsøøø       Syntax is shown below for each of the Draper Pascal reservedø       words.  The complete manual provided to registered users, however,ø       contains COMPLETE definitions, COMPLETE sample programsø       demonstrating the use of each reserved word, as well as BASICø       equivalents.øø       ABS                FUNCTION ABS(Number):INTEGER;øø       ADDR               FUNCTION ADDR(Var):INTEGER;øø       ANDøø       ARCTAN             FUNCTION ARCTAN(Var):REAL;øø       ARRAY              ARRAY[Number1] OF Typeø                          ARRAY[Number1,Number2] OF Typeøø       ASC                FUNCTION ASC(Cvar):INTEGER;øø       BEGINøø       BLOAD              PROCEDURE BLOAD(Program);øø       BOOLEANøø       CALL               PROCEDURE CALL(Address);øø       CASE               CASE expr1 OF const1 : stmt1;ø                                        const2 : stmt2;ø                                        ...ø                                        constn : stmtnø                          END;øø                          CASE expr1 OF const1 : stmt1;ø                                        const2 : stmt2;ø                                        ...ø                                        constn : stmtnø                          ELSE stmtxø                          END;øøø       CHARøø       CHR                FUNCTION CHR(expr1):CHAR;øø       CLOSE              PROCEDURE CLOSE(File);øø       COLOR              PROCEDURE COLOR(Number);øøøøøø                                       27øøøøø       Draper Pascal 2.1                             Pascal Definitionsøøøøø       CONCAT             PROCEDURE CONCAT(Parm1,Parm2,...):STRING;øø       CONST              CONST name1=value1; name2=value2; ...øø       COPY               FUNCTION COPY(Source,Index,Length) : STRING;øø       COS                FUNCTION COS(Var):REAL;øø       CVTREAL            FUNCTION CVTREAL(Ivar):REALøø       DEG                PROCEDURE DEG;øø       DELETE             PROCEDURE DELETE(Source,Index,Size);øø       DIVøø       DOS                PROCEDURE DOS;øø       DRAWTO             PROCEDURE DRAWTO(X,Y);øø       DUMPSTK            PROCEDURE DUMPSTK;øø       DVSTAT             PROCEDURE DVSTAT(A,B,C,D);øø       ENDøø       EOF                EOF(File);øø       EOLN               EOLN(File);øø       EXIT               PROCEDURE EXIT;øø       EXP                FUNCTION EXP(Var):REAL;øø       EXP10              FUNCTION EXP10(Var):REAL;øø       FALSEøø       FILEøø       FOR                FOR var := expr1 TO expr2 DO statement;ø                          FOR var := expr1 DOWNTO expr2 DO statement;øø       FUNCTIONøø       GOTOXY             PROCEDURE GOTOXY(X,Y);øø       GRAPHICS           PROCEDURE GRAPHICS(Number);øø       HIMEM              PROCEDURE HIMEM(Value);øøøøøøø                                       28øøøøø       Draper Pascal 2.1                             Pascal Definitionsøøøøø       IF                 IF expr1 THEN stmt1;ø                          IF expr1 THEN stmt1 ELSE stmt2;øø       INSERT             PROCEDURE INSERT(Source,Destination,Index);øø       INTEGERøø       IORESULT           FUNCTION IORESULT:INTEGER;øø       KEYPRESS           FUNCTION KEYPRESS:INTEGER;øø       LENGTH             FUNCTION LENGTH(svar):INTEGER;øø       LN                 FUNCTION LN(Var):REAL;øø       LOCATE             FUNCTION LOCATE(X,Y):INTEGER;øø       LOCK               PROCEDURE LOCK(Filename);øø       LOG                FUNCTION LOG(Var):REAL;øø       LPENH, LPENV       FUNCTION LPENH:INTEGER;ø                          FUNCTION LPENV:INTEGER;øø       MAXGRAPH           PROCEDURE MAXGRAPH(Mode);øø       MODøø       NOTøø       NOTE               PROCEDURE NOTE(Iocbno,Sector,Byte);øø       ODD                FUNCTION ODD(iexp);øø       OPEN               PROCEDURE OPEN(Fileno,Aux1,Aux2,Filename);;øø       OPTIONKEYøø       OPTIONS            OPTIONS(Opt1,Opt2,...,Optn);øø       ORøø       ORD                FUNCTION ORD(Realvar):INTEGER;øø       PADDLE             FUNCTION PADDLE(Number):INTEGER;øø       PEEK               FUNCTION PEEK(Address):INTEGER;øø       PLOT               PROCEDURE PLOT(X,Y);øø       POINT              PROCEDURE POINT(Iocbno,Sector,Byte);øøøøøø                                       29øøøøø       Draper Pascal 2.1                             Pascal Definitionsøøøøø       POKE               PROCEDURE POKE(Address,Value);øø       POS                FUNCTION POS(Pattern,Source):INTEGER;øø       PROCEDURE          PROCEDURE Name;ø                          PROCEDURE Name(Parm1,Parm2,...,Parmn);øø       PROGRAM            PROGRAM Name;øø       PTRIG              FUNCTION PTRIG(Number):INTEGER;øø       PURGE              PROCEDURE PURGE(Filespec);øø       RADøø       READ, READLN       PROCEDURE READ(File,Var1,Var2,...Varn);øø       REALøø       RECORDøø       REPEAT             REPEAT Stmt1; ... ;Stmtn UNTIL Condition;øø       RESET              PROCEDURE RESET(File,Filespec);øø       REWRITE            PROCEDURE REWRITE(File,Filespec);øø       RND                FUNCTION RND(Iexp):INTEGER;øø       SELECTKEYøø       SETCOLOR           PROCEDURE SETCOLOR(Register,Hue,Luminance);øø       SHL                Expr1 SHL Expr2øø       SHR                Expr1 SHR Expr2øø       SIN                FUNCTION SIN(Var):REAL;øø       SOUND              PROCEDURE SOUND(Voice,Pitch,Distortion,Volume);øøø       SQR                FUNCTION SQR(Var):REAL;øø       SQRT               FUNCTION SQRT(Var):REAL;øø       STARTKEYøø       STATUS             PROCEDURE STATUS(Iocbno,Ivar);øø       STICK              FUNCTION STICK(Number):INTEGER;øøøøøø                                       30øøøøø       Draper Pascal 2.1                             Pascal Definitionsøøøøø       STR                FUNCTION STR(Var):STRING;øø       STRIG              FUNCTION STRIG(Number):INTEGER;øø       STRINGøø       TRACEOFF           PROCEDURE TRACEOFF;øø       TRACEON            PROCEDURE TRACEON;ø                          PROCEDURE TRACEON('Number);øø       TRUEøø       UNLOCK             PROCEDURE UNLOCK(Filespec);øø       VAL                FUNCTION VAL(Svar):INTEGER or REAL;øø       VAR                VAR Name1,Name2,...,Namen : Type;ø                          VAR Name1,Name2,...,Namen : ARRAY[Number]ø                              OF Type;øø       WAIT               PROCEDURE WAIT(Number);øø       WHILE              WHILE Condition DO Statement;øø       WRITE              WRITE(File,Expr1,Expr2,...);ø                          WRITE(File,Expr1:Fldwdth...);ø                          WRITE(File,Expr1:Fldwdth:Numdec...);øø       WRITELN            WRITELN(File,Expr1,Expr2,...);ø                          WRITELN(File,Expr1:Fldwdth...);ø                          WRITELN(File,Expr1:Fldwdth:Numdec...);øø       XCTL               PROCEDURE XCTL(Filespec);øø       XIO                PROCEDURE XIO(Number,File,Aux1,Aux2,Filespec);øøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøø                                       31øøøøø       Draper Pascal 2.1                             System Informationøøøøø                               System Informationøø       The Supervisor uses zero page locations $A0 - $BF. Locations $80 -ø       $9F are available for your use if desired. Various locationsø       between $D4 and $FD are used by the floating point routines. Pageø       six ($600 - $6FF) is available for your use and not used by theø       Pascal system.øø       The Supervisor is loaded into memory by DOS at the address $1D7C.ø       If this memory location is not available, then an error message isø       given, along with an explanation of the probable cause of theø       problem. The pseudo code program to be executed is loaded inø       memory immediately after the end of the Supervisor. The pseudoø       machine stack extends from the end of the pseudo code program toø       the MEMTOP position, just before screen memory.øøø                             Filename Descriptionsøøø       The files named below are included in this ARC file:øø       AUTORUN.SYS             Supervisor object codeø       COMPILER.PCD            Compiler pcodeø       EDITOR.PCD              Editor pcodeø       INIT.PCD                Main Menu pcodeø       INIT.PAS                Main Menu Pascal sourceø       EXPLNERR.PCD            Error code explainor (used by Compiler)ø       RSVDWRDS.TXT            Reserved word list (used by Compiler)ø       ERRORS.TXT              Text for compile errors (used byø                                 EXPLNERR.PCD)ø       RAMDISK1.DAT            Ramdisk setup (See complete manual)ø       RAMDISK2.DAT            Ramdisk setup (See complete manual)ø       RAMDISK3.DAT            Ramdisk setup (See complete manual)ø       NOTITLE.OBJ             Used to suppress title (See completeø                                 manual)ø       SAMPLE1.PAS             Kaleidoscope sample program sourceø       SAMPLE2.PAS             Roman numeral sample program sourceø       PASCAL.DOC              This introduction manualøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøø                                       32øøøøø       Draper Pascal 2.1                             Reserved Word Listøøøøø                               Reserved Word Listøø       ABS      DEG       FUNCTION  ODD       READLN    STRINGø       ADDR     DELETE    GOTOXY    OF        REAL      THENø       AND      DIV       GRAPHICS  OPEN      RECORD    TOø       ARCTAN   DO        HIMEM     OPTIONKEY REPEAT    TRACEOFFø       ARRAY    DOS       IF        OPTIONS   RESET     TRACEONø       ASC      DOWNTO    INSERT    OR        REWRITE   TRUEø       BEGIN    DRAWTO    INTEGER   ORD       RND       UNLOCKø       BLOAD    DUMPSTK   IORESULT  PADDLE    SELECTKEY UNTILø       BOOLEAN  DVSTAT    KEYPRESS  PEEK      SETCOLOR  VALø       CALL     ELSE      LENGTH    PLOT      SHL       VARø       