Number expectedø      03: '=' expectedø      04: Identifier expectedø      05: Constant type identifier, number, or string constant expectedø      06: 'BEGIN' expectedø      07: Too many nesting levelsø      08: ':' expectedø      09: '.' expectedø      10: ';' expectedø      11: Undeclared identifierø      12: Invalid type of identifierø      13: ':=' expectedø      14: 'END' expectedø      15: ';', 'ELSE', or 'END' expectedø      16: 'THEN' expectedø      17: '#' expectedø      18: 'DO' expectedø      19: '#' or FILE type identifier expectedø      20: '[' expectedø      21: ']' expectedø      22: ')' expectedø      23: Illegal factor or identifier typeø      24: INCLUDE file nesting too deepø      25:ø      26: 'OF' expectedø      27: Mismatched data typesø      28: 'TO' or 'DOWNTO' expectedø      29: 'UNTIL' expectedø      30: Range errorø      31: '(' expectedø      32: ',' expectedø      33: Literal too long or missing end quote (')ø      34: 'END' but no RECORD startedø      35: Incorrect number of parametersø      36: INTEGER type identifier expectedø      37: STRING type identifier expectedø      38: REAL type identifier expectedø      39: CHAR type identifier expectedø      40: FILE type identifier expectedø      41: HEX type identifier expectedø      42: STRING constant expectedøøøøøøøøøøø                                       35øøøøø       Draper Pascal 2.1                                 Error Messagesøøøøøø                         EXECUTION TIME ERROR MESSAGESøø       INDEX TOO HIGHøø                           This message occurs if an attempt is made toø                           store a string array element into an occuranceø                           that is higher than defined for the variable.ø                           For example, if you tried to store theø                           twentieth entry of an array that was onlyø                           defined to hold ten occurances, you would getø                           the message. This message only applies toø                           string arrays since other array types are notø                           checked for valid occurance numbers.øøø       UNABLE TO OPEN DEBUG IOCB (7)øø                           This message is issued if the list outputø                           device you specify in response to the 'WHERE?ø                           (FILESPEC)' prompt cannot be opened. Theø                           prompt is issued only for the debug featuresø                           trace and stack display.øøø       CIO ERROR xxx FOR IOCB # yøø                           Some kind of Input-Output operation wasø                           performed which resulted in an abnormal returnø                           code from the Atari operating system. Refer toø                           your BASIC or DOS manual for the meaning ofø                           the error number 'xxx'. 'y' is the IOCB numberø                           which the error occured on. Note that thisø                           message will not be printed if OPTIONS(0) isø                           in effect. In this case it is yourø                           responsibility to check the return code byø                           interrogating IORESULT after each I/O typeø                           instruction.øøø       AT OFFSETøø                           This message accompanies some other errorø                           message and refers to the offset within theø                           pseudo code of the instruction that had theø                           error. Refer to the offset shown on yourø                           compile listing to determine the Pascalø                           instruction that experienced the error.øøøøøøøøø                                       36øøøøø       Draper Pascal 2.1                                 Error Messagesøøøøø       STOPPED BY <BREAK> KEYøø                           This message indicates that execution of theø                           program was stopped because the BREAK key wasø                           pressed. The offset of the instructionø                           executing is shown in the 'AT OFFSET' message.ø                           Note that this message will not occur (and theø                           program will not stop after BREAK is pressed)ø                           if OPTIONS(4) is in effect.øøø       INSUFFICIENT MEMORYøø                           This message indicates that an attempt wasø                           made to increase the value of the stackø                           pointer to a value which would overlay screenø                           memory or the trace buffer, if the trace wasø                           active. It may also be caused by manipulationø                           of a record without sufficient room betweenø                           the top of the stack and the top of availableø                           memory (MEMTOP) to temporarily hold it.øøø       INVALID OPCODEøø                           This message should not occur. It indicatesø                           that a pseudo instruction was encounteredø                           which is invalid. If you get this message, itø                           means that your '.PCD' file has been corruptedø                           somehow or an XCTL was made to a file that wasø                           not a pseudo code file. To correct, re-compileø                           the program in question. It may also occur ifø                           you attempt to run a Draper Pascal programø                           which was compiled under a previous release ofø                           this software.øøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøøø                                       37øøøøø       Draper Pascal 2.1                              Registration Formøøøøø                               Registration Formøø       When you register for a fee of only $15.00, you will receive aø       copy of the latest version of the Draper Pascal manual.  Also, ifø       a later version of the software is more current than the versionø       you are registering, you will receive a diskette containing it.ø       In addition to all relative information in this manual, theø       complete manual provided to registered users contains theø       following:øø       *  Complete Draper Pascal reserved word definitionsøø       *  Complete Draper Pascal example programs demonstrating the useø          of each reserved wordøø       *  BASIC equivalents for each reserved word, where applicableøø       *  Information on setup and use of a Ramdisk for Draper Pascal.ø          After proper initialization, the Editor will take less than twoø          seconds to load and the Compiler will take less than threeø          seconds.  Also, the default drive will be automatically set toø          the Ramdisk.øø       *  A royalty-free, non-exclusive license to allow you toø          distribute software developed using Draper Pascaløø       *  Complete Draper Pascal source listings for the Editor, Mainø          Menu program, Ramdisk initialization program, and sampleø          programsøø       *  Editor command summaryøø       *  Information on how to suppress the title screen from beingø          displayedøø       *  Trace format descriptionsøø       *  Internal data format descriptionsøø       *  Notes on printer usage with Draper Pascaløø       *  Technical support, by mail, at no chargeøøø       If you purchased Draper Pascal directly from Draper Software inø       your own name, then your copy is already registered and you willø       recieve all the benefits of registration.  You do not need to sendø       in a registration form.øø       If you received Draper Pascal some other way, you may registerø       your copy by filling out the following form and mailing it to theø       listed address along with your check or money order.øøøøø                                       38øøøøø       Draper Pascal 2